Excellent! I found the pattern at lines 2259-2284. The code already has a comment describing the optimization:

```
// C - ((A - X) & M) -> X & (2*C + M) if C == A & M and A & ~M == ~M
// This uses the identity: when A has all low bits (of ~M) set,
// (A - X) & M = C - (X & ~M) where C = A & M.
// Then C - ((A - X) & M) = C - (C - (X & ~M)) = X & ~M.
// But ~M is relative to A's width, so the result is X & (C + (A & ~M)).
// Since A & ~M = ~M (in low bits) and C = A & M, we get X & (C + ~M_low).
// Example: 64 - ((71 - X) & -8) = X & 120 because 64 = 71 & -8, 
//          71 & 7 = 7, and 64 + 56 = 120 where 56 = 71 - 15.
// Simplified: result = X & (2*C + M) when conditions hold.
```

This is exactly the pattern we need! The example in the comment even matches our test case: `64 - ((71 - X) & -8) = X & 120`.

Let me look at the pattern matching more closely:
```cpp
